issue_title: Is it possible to support Paging concept introduced in recent year?
issue_body:
- [x] I have verified there are no duplicate open or recent questions.
- [x] I have read over the documentation, checked out the examples and the demo app.
- [x] I have given my issue a non-generic title.
- [x] I understand that if I ask the same question in [stackoverflow](http://www.stackoverflow.com) website I will get answers way faster as more people will try to answer it.
- [x] I understand that if I don't show a minimum effort of what I have tried and where I got stuck the question will be closed and marked as invalid.
- [x] I have read the article [How do I ask a good question?](https://stackoverflow.com/help/how-to-ask)
- [x] I understand that this library is a custom [Adapter](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/support/v7/widget/RecyclerView.Adapter.html) and **NOT** a custom [RecyclerView](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/support/v7/widget/RecyclerView.html). I understand the difference between them and what is possible to be done in an Adapter but not in a RecyclerView.

I really like the `addSection` concept provided by this library.

In recent year, Google introduced Paging concept. Instead of having to load entire data from database into memory, then present it in RecyclerView. User can now choose to only load a very small subset of data, during RecyclerView scrolling. 

Google achieves so by introducing
- https://developer.android.com/reference/android/arch/paging/PagedListAdapter
- `LiveData<PageList<...>>` returned by Room DB

The key concept, is to call `submitList` in `PagedListAdapter`, whenever the new subset of data is available, during scrolling.

A nice introduction video during Google I/O 2018 is available - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BE5bsyGGLf4

Currently, I cannot see a direct way, how we can fit such `submitList` paging concept, into `SectionedRecyclerViewAdapter`. 

I was wondering, do you have any idea how we can achieve Section concept, yet able to provide paging capability?

Thank you.

issue_title: Add UI elements for comment position and margin
Desktop: Content script plugins don't ship with external js libraries
issue_body:
When an external library is accessed through a contentScript it isn't packaged up on `npm run dist`. This means that it won't be distributed with the plugin, and any attempt to run the plugin from a jpl file will crash Joplin.

I tried requiring the library from the index.ts script. This correctly included the module in the dist files, but was only accessible to the index file. I think the same system of including libraries probably needs to be adapted for contentScripts.

I pushed [my project](https://github.com/CalebJohn/joplin-math-mode) to github so it can be used to reproduce the issue.

## Environment

Joplin version: master (4180d4bd28f2e5317e347b6262d58c0ed0c8b47f)
Platform: Linux Desktop 
OS specifics: Ubuntu 20.04



## Steps to reproduce

1. Create a plugin that uses a contentScript (CodeMirror in my case)
2. Access an external library through that plugin (mathjs in my case)
3. run `npm run dist` and attempt to use the plugin with the resulting jpl file
4. Observe that Joplin crashes because the library is unavailable

issue_title: [CLOUD] Fix KeyError: 'accountId' in cloud when customer already exists
issue_body:
```
2020-02-29 22:28:54,346 - ERROR - bulk_customer_import.bulk_customer_import - Failed to process row: ['Super Company', 'John Smith', 'john.smith@example.com']
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/Users/simon/Development/jsd-bulk-customer-upload/bulk_customer_import/bulk_customer_import.py", line 108, in main
    client.organization.add_customer(organization, customer)
  File "/Users/simon/Development/jsd-bulk-customer-upload/bulk_customer_import/organization.py", line 28, in add_customer
    data = {fields[0]: [customer[fields[1]]]}
KeyError: 'accountId'
```

In jira service desk cloud you need to use the customer account ID when adding a customer to the organization.

If the customer doesn't exist in jira yet then there is no issue because the account ID is returned in the data from creating a new customer via the API and can subsequently be referenced in order to add the customer to an organisation.

However if the customer already exists in jira, then the account creation step will fail due to trying to create a duplicate user and then we dont have the accountId.

We need to go and get the account ID for an existing customer.

This shouldn't be too hard in cloud but this completely breaks compatability with server and the script will need to be rearchiteched to support the processes required for these two diverging platforms respectively.

issue_title: bug in Pandas when reading files with 'Infinity'
issue_body:
By default this fork of QtPlaskin uses pandas.read_csv  function to speed up data loading.
ZdPlaskin is a Fortran code and uses "Infinity" to represent inf values in output text files.
There is an [issue #10065](https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/issues/10065) in Pandas with reading such files. Pandas read_csv interprets "Infinity" as a string, not a floating point value.

Untill  the issue #10065 is not resolved in Pandas, as a workaround, we fallback to old (slower) data import for datasets containing "Infinity"s. [a5b1559](https://github.com/erwanp/qtplaskin/commit/a5b1559393f5041686ae6956e66a3c71ed49ba90)   

**Update**: Add a very straightforward fix to Pandas [#28181](https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/28181). Hope, someone will come up with smarter solution.  

 - [x] Get https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/28181 be merged
-  [x] Wait for Pandas release
-  [x] Fix tests (remove `xfail`) 
-  [x] Update `setup.py` https://github.com/erwanp/qtplaskin/blob/1aeb4a7ec618a3be10447c8e18b7b03a6b2ecf69/setup.py#L48-L56

issue_title: Add new inpainting flags
Travel money check shows warning when exact money is carried
Regex flags aren't taken into consideration
issue_body:
Regex flags aren't passed to regex101 causing it to default to `global` and `multi-line`.

```js
// JavaScript / TypeScript
const pattern = /[abc]/i;
```
The regex above should open the following URL: `https://regex101.com?regex=%5Babc%5D&flavor=javascript&flags=i`, but opens `https://regex101.com?regex=%5Babc%5D&flavor=javascript`.

Every language does flags differently, so fixing this would probably require some smart traversal of PSI elements based on the language, which in turn would probably require different implementations based on the available plugins.

Maybe it's better to just default to `&flags=` (no flags)?

Here are some more examples that should all pass `&flags=i`:
```kt
// Kotlin
val pattern = Regex("[abc]", RegexOption.IGNORE_CASE)
```
```java
// Java
Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile("[abc]", Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE);
```
```python
# Python
pattern = re.compile("[abc]", re.IGNORECASE)
```

issue_title: Attempting to match globs finds no files
issue_body:
Using the example in the readme for avoiding matching `.spec.lua` files or modified ones like `stylua -g **/*.lua -g !**/*.spec.lua .` just returns `error: no files provided`. Ideally this should match against regular `.lua` files that are discoverable in the path given.

This seems to be related to the glob option matching multiple patterns following it and the path to run on being treated as a glob. `stylua -g **/*.lua .` has this problem, but `stylua -g **/*.lua --check .` does not.

issue_body:
예언
1넴(방패병 메아리): 다리, 직방, 이켈핸캐, 과부의 아픔
2넴(정육면체): 팔, 살무사, 여백의 미
3넴(켈 메아리): 달송곳니 방어구 5중 1
클리어 상자: 머리, 가슴, 직방, 이켈샷건, 교도소

구원의 정원
1넴(축성의 정신 회피): 축적된 구원, 광신도의 보상, 다리
2넴(축성의 정신 소환): 무모한 오라클, 파멸의 예언자, 팔
3넴(축성의 정신 처치): 신성한 기원, 고대의 복음, 가슴
4넴(신성한 정신 처치): 전지적인 눈, 머리, 직업
퀘스트: 신성

딥스톤 무덤
1넴(무덤 보안 우회): 팔, 다리, 직업, 수탁자
2넴(아트락스-1 처치): 팔, 다리, 직업, 상속, 계승
3넴(강하 생존): 가슴, 팔, 직업, 후세
4넴(괴인 타닉스 처치): 머리, 가슴, 다리, 유증, 기념
딥스톤 무덤 클리어 시 랜덤: 내일의 눈

마지막 소원
태고의 결속, 변신, 야수들의 나라, 천국의 독재자, 수다쟁이 뼈, 최고의 포식자, 패권, 테키언 부대
1넴(칼리 처치): 걸작 태고의 결속
2넴(슈로 치 처치): 걸작 변신
3넴(탑의 수호자 모르게스 처치): 걸작 야수들의 나라
4넴(금고 열기): 걸작 천국의 독재자
5넴(천의 목소리를 내는 리븐 처치): 걸작 수다쟁이 뼈
마지막 소원 클리어 시 랜덤: 천의 목소리

issue_body:
In #499, I disabled latest Edge for unit and UI tests, while keeping some of them on Edge 44 (which is the current latest) and Edge 40 (which is the one used on Windows mobile).
The reason is I needed to disable some UI tests on Edge<=44, but did not find an easy way to know the version of the tested browser, at runtime.

When Microsoft releases the new Edge based on Chromium, we should re-enable latest Edge in .travis.yml (where it starts nightwatch).
It should behave like Chromium, so we will probably not need to disable any tests for it.

issue_title: [question] how to use dali resize in "not_larger" mode?
issue_body:
Hi there, for example, here i have two images, image_a with shape (500,500,3) and image_b with shape (1100,750,3).
I use "not_larger" mode in ops.Resize, like below:
`resize = ops.Resize(device='cpu', mode="not_larger", size=960)`
and the output shapes are image_a with shape (960,960,3) and image_b with shape (960,655,3) .
I want to know where there is any method to keep the origin shape when the longer size in one image is smaller than 960.
In other words i want to resize image_b to (960,655,3) because its too larger, but i want to keep image_a as the shape it used to be, and that is (500,500,3).

issue_title: Object processor queue starts too early
issue_body:
Received a report. Looks like `objectProcessor` starts before `sqlThread` is ready. I can't actually reproduce it, it probably only happens ~if the `objectProcessorQueue` isn't empty~ under non-deterministic conditions. The problem was revealed in 184664d7583096e6cd7b828e08d112ff1727d81b. The solution is for the `objectProcessor.__init__` to wait for the `helper_sql.sql_ready` event.

issue_title: Field ordering in introspection queries
issue_body:
Hi, I see that as of #594 the fields of a type in a schema are always ordered alphabetically. This is somewhat confusing with a schema-first approach to a server as the fields are all out of order from their originally shared schema. Could we please make this behaviour optional? It would make sense to me to control ordering by providing the user a setter for an `IComparer<FieldType>` which defaults to the original ordering and having a "ByName" implementation provided OOTB to smooth the common case.

Or at the very least can the behaviour be opt-out if not opt-in?

issue_title: Building with "-o /dev/null" when the input is cached triggers an assert
issue_body:
1. build ccache 4.1-master (238553a1c470)
2.  export CCACHE_DIR=$PWD/foo; mkdir foo
3. echo 'void f() {}' > foo.c
4. ./ccache gcc -c foo.c -o foo.o  # fill cache
5. ./ccache gcc -c foo.c -o foo.o  # use cache (works fine, not required to trigger the bug)
6. ./ccache gcc -c foo.c -o /dev/null

This triggers an assert:

`ccache: ResultRetriever.cpp:129: virtual void ResultRetriever::on_entry_data(const uint8_t *, size_t): failed assertion:
(m_dest_file_type == FileType::stderr_output && !m_dest_fd) || (m_dest_file_type != FileType::stderr_output && m_dest_fd)`

issue_title: I don't understand how to avoid using a function-scoped fixture
issue_body:
TLDR: getting this warning and don't know what to do about it:

`HypothesisDeprecationWarning: tests/test_xlwings2.py::test_cos_with_floats uses the 'cos_sheet' fixture, which is reset between function calls but not between test cases generated by `@given(...)`.  You can change it to a module- or session-scoped fixture if it is safe to reuse; if not we recommend using a context manager inside your test function.  See https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/fixture.html#sharing-test-data for details on fixture scope.`

-----

What I'm trying to do:

There is a Python library called [xlcalculator](https://github.com/bradbase/xlcalculator). It's supposed to be an implementation of the Excel calculation engine but entirely in Python and open-source, so you can integrate live spreadsheet models with Python's data science infrastructure, even in environments without an MS Office install. So, it is important that the Python implementations of formulae match the Excel implementations as closely as possible. There are a lot of undocumented quirks in Excel, which have to be discovered through experimentation.

There is another library called [xlwings](https://www.xlwings.org/). This lets you use Python to "drive" an open Excel instance, like what VBA can do. This is where hypothesis comes in. If we have an Excel formula, e.g. `COS`, and a corresponding Python function `COS`, we want to test the property that the latter matches the former's behaviour exactly (i.e. the Excel implementation is an oracle). So a test would proceed as follows:

- Launch an Excel process and open a workbook
- In the workbook, set up one cell (say, A1) to be the "input" cell, and another cell (say, B1) to be the output cell. the former would be left blank, the latter would have the formula `=COS(A1)` entered
- Use Hypothesis to generate floating point numbers. For each float `x`, enter it in cell A1, then record the new value of cell B1.
- Compare this value to the Python implementation of `COS(x)`. If they differ, fail the test.
- Once we are done with the function, clean up by closing the workbook. Make a new workbook to test a new formula, repeat.
- Once we are done with the test session, kill the Excel process

Here is code that does this (Windows only, and you need Excel installed):

```python
from contextlib import contextmanager
import math

import xlwings as xw
import pytest
from hypothesis import given, settings
from hypothesis.strategies import floats


# this is really slow so we only want to do it once per session
@pytest.fixture(scope="session")
def excel_app():
    app = xw.App(add_book=False)
    try:
        yield app
    finally:
        app.kill()


@contextmanager
def excel_workbook(app):
    wb = app.books.add()
    try:
        yield wb
    finally:
        wb.close()


# we use a different fixture for each different formula (with the boilerplate suitably abstracted away), but the fixture is reused across `hypothesis.given` examples within each `test_xxxx` function
@pytest.fixture
def cos_sheet(excel_app)
    with excel_workbook(excel_app) as wb:
        sheet = wb.sheets["Sheet1"]
        sheet["B1"].value = "=COS(A1)"
        yield sheet


# python implementation of excel formula
def COS(x):
    return math.cos(x)


@given(value=floats(allow_nan=False, allow_infinity=False))
@settings(deadline=None)
def test_cos_with_floats(value, cos_sheet):
    # arrange
    cos_sheet["A1"].value = value # insert given float into the spreadsheet
    expected = cos_sheet["B1"].value # observe the result
    
    # act
    result = COS(value)

    # assert
    assert math.isclose(result, expected)
```

(And this does actually produce a counterexample: [it fails on inputs above 2^27](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15579897/why-does-cos227-fail), which is a limitation not mentioned in the Microsoft documentation)

But it gives the warning:

`HypothesisDeprecationWarning: tests/test_xlwings2.py::test_cos_with_floats uses the 'cos_sheet' fixture, which is reset between function calls but not between test cases generated by `@given(...)`.  You can change it to a module- or session-scoped fixture if it is safe to reuse; if not we recommend using a context manager inside your test function.  See https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/fixture.html#sharing-test-data for details on fixture scope.`

I can't make sense of this. I *want* it to not be reset between test cases generated by `given`, because closing and making a new workbook is an expensive operation. It's totally impractical to do it anew for every single generated random float, so it has to be reused. But I *don't want* it to be module-scoped, because I don't want to share the workbooks *between* `test_` functions, because they all need a slightly different cell setup (e.g. different number of arguments, auxiliary cells to handle errors, etc). If I made it module-scoped, I'd need to make a separate little module for every single test function, and that's absurd. And I don't know what kind of context manager would help me here.

So, what do I do? I understand that this warning [is soon going to become an error](https://github.com/HypothesisWorks/hypothesis/issues/2709#issuecomment-751335212), so I need to find out the "proper" way of handling this situation.

issue_title: Item price visual comparison on "Selling" tab
issue_body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Not necessarily a problem, but I tend to have a character with a ton of transmog items in the bags. Some of the pieces I want to sell, and some that are not worth selling i want to use for my own transmog unlock or sell to vendor. This is a hassle when I have all of my bags full with gear pieces as I have no visual indication what is worth more than the rest and i have to hover or click on each item 1 by 1 and decide then if it is worth selling.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
If possible to implement - i would like to see some kind of colored indicator (example: dot/line over the item icon that changes color gradually - perhaps red to green spectrum?). this indicator would compare the prices of all items currently in the bag/"selling" tab between each other and be colored accordingly. This would be based on single items, ignoring the quantities.
Of course this could also be a toggle in the options for users who do not want to see this or need this option.

This would also give you a better visualization on what is worth farming more compared to other things (possibly extend outside the selling tab to your bags with a toggle?)

Im not sure if this is a good idea or is feasible but i just wanted to leave my feedback here as this is one of the only gripes I have when posting a million transmogs / different types of herbs ores etc. to AH

Thank you so much for the great addon, I will be using it always even if this is not implement <3

issue_title: Small elapsed time on Render() when vsync is enabled
issue_body:
# Summary
When VSync is on, the elapsed time passed to the Render() method is typically a very low value on some machines (in mine, 0.00001 to 0.001, which is waaay lower than the ~0.016 expected with a window configured to 60fps).

(When VSync is turned off, in my machine the elapsed time is around 0.016 as expected).

# Steps to reproduce
- Platform: Desktop
- NET Version: .NET 5
- API: OpenGL 3.3

I set up a small project to try to reproduce the problem. To run, download the 2.0 release Silk.NET.OpenGL, Windowing and Input packages and run a project with nothing but [this Program.cs file](https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/607634593201520651/795043831732764742/Program.cs) (don't worry, it's quite small 😉)

# Comments
Since this problem doesn't seem to be happening to anyone but me, I will investigate this issue further.

issue_title: Implement since
issue_body:
ASH has a neat [`since`](https://wiki.kolmafia.us/index.php/Since) statement that checks KoLmafia's version. Unfortunately it's a custom statement, not a built-in function, so the JS runtime doesn't have it.

I made a utility library, [kolmafia-util](https://github.com/pastelmind/kolmafia-util), that replicates this feature in JS. It would be nice to integrate it into libram.

## Proposal

Add two functions:
```ts
function sinceKolmafiaVersion(majorVersion: number, minorVersion: number): void;
function sinceKolmafiaRevision(revision: number): void;
```

These would throw a `KolmafiaVersionError` if the current version/revision is less than the required amount.

## How about implementing it in KoLmafia's JS Runtime?

* Extending the JS syntax with a `since` statement will break TS/JS tools
* Adding an ASH/JS library function in KoLmafia would be easy, but it would be redundant with the existing `since` statement.

issue_title: Use custom batch dataloader with DDP
issue_body:
Hello,
In our project, we use a custom data loader like so:
```
class BatchDataLoader(torch.utils.data.dataloader.DataLoader):
    def __init__(self, ds, batch_size, shuffle, num_workers=0):
        inner_sampler = RandomSampler(ds) if shuffle else SequentialSampler(ds)
        sampler = BatchSampler(inner_sampler, batch_size, False)
        super().__init__(ds, batch_size=None, sampler=sampler, num_workers=num_workers)
```

We use this custom dataloader so that the `__getitem__` method is directly called with the list of batch indices and returns a full batch instead of single items. We need this because for some technical reasons, the `__getitem__` method is way way faster when accessing a batch of data items rather than single ones. This has been working perfectly fine so far until we started looking into using ddp for training our model.

By default Lightning setup its own sampler for distributed training. We can override this behaviour with replace_sampler_ddp=False but then our custom sampler would be used, whereas it is not made for distributing.

If we wish to make our own custom distributed version of it, then how can we retrieve the distributed context from lightning? Is there a way to know if we are in a distributed context, and if so, how many nodes, etc? Can this be done from a Lightning data module, as this is where we instantiate the data loaders? I tried using `torch.distributed,is_available()` as a first step. While this passes on Windows, this call fails with `AssertionError: Default process group is not initialized` on Linux if we are not in a distrbuted context (for instance training on a single GPU). For info, I'm using Lightning 1.0.5 with PyTorch 1.5.1. We wish to setup our sampler automatically, without the user having to specify extra parameters.

Or do you see a way to achieve the same behaviour (getting batches of indices in the `__getitem__` method of the dataset) while still benefitting from the default DistributedSampler that Lightning setup? I thought of wrapping my original dataset in another one that would create "buckets" of data, but then how can I make sure the dataset is reshuffled each epoch so that the buckets don't always have the same content?

Thanks for your help :)

issue_title: unix shell crash with path segment  on Windows when CWD is root of drive
issue_body:
### Prerequisites

- [ ] I have read and understand the `CONTRIBUTING` guide
- [x ] I looked for duplicate issues before submitting this one

### Description

If I use a "path" segment as in jandedobbeleer.omp.json and CD into the root of a drive, tcsh crashes.

This is because the path segment generates a ```"\"``` as the path and immediately follows it with "%{" for the next segment. However, in tcsh the resulting string is ```"\%"``` , which escapes the literal quoting of the following ANSI escape sequence, causing all kinds of havoc of unescaped characters.

**I am not sure if this is restricted to tcsh, since I would expect ZSH to have the same behavior.**  

I can see two possible solutions:  
1. Generate ```"\\"``` instead of ```"\"```, to escape the backslash. This should work.
2. Generate "/" instead.  The Windows-native version of tcsh  only uses "/" for paths, but I have no idea if that will mess up the various cygwin shells.

I can work around this for now by not using a path segment, since I prefer using tcshs "%c0n" syntax for paths in prompt anyway.

thanks!

issue_title: Request: option to use non-"logical" sort order
issue_body:
System: Win8.1 x64
Explorer++ version 1.3.5.531 (32-bit Unicode build) of 03/02/2013 21:13:37

First of all, nice work!  Second, I would like to request an option to use the non-"logical" sort order for sorting by name.  

Conditions: I have a directory with filenames starting with "18," "19," "1A," and "1B."  
Observed behaviour: The "1A" and "1B" sort before the "18" and "19" because the number 1 is smaller than 18 or 19.  This is the behaviour of [StrCmpLogicalW](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb759947%28VS.85%29.aspx) (see [this answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/4314191/2877364) by [hmuelner](http://stackoverflow.com/users/324065/hmuelner)).  
Requested behaviour: "1A" should sort after "19".  Specifically, would it be possible to use [StrCmpI](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb759942%28v=vs.85%29.aspx) instead per an option setting?  It appears to be in [ShellBrowser/SortManager.cpp](https://github.com/derceg/explorerplusplus/blob/43e90624af673254e43c2aaf898f2c81eab5ff9d/Explorer%2B%2B/ShellBrowser/SortManager.cpp) lines 338, 379, and 386 (plus elsewhere, but those don't appear relevant to my specific request).

Thank you for your consideration!

issue_title: Error and server hanging out pasting a schematic with AsyncWe

**Describe the bug**
A clear and concise description of what the bug is.

> Got an error during schematic pasting process with AsyncWorldEdit.
> Moreover, chunk loading was stuck and the server couldn't be stopped correctly (thread dumps appeared).

> I didn't reproduce the issue a second time, however, such an issue can completely crash a server, even probably corrupt data as it stuck the server and lighting system => it seemed better to me to inform you about it then.

**To Reproduce**

> Try to paste a schematic with AsyncWorldEdit and just wait / move around to load, unload chunks. This error just randomly poped and I didn't find a consistent cause :/

- aoc-bot
- aoc-data

The aoc-data should not depend on serenity. Curently, it does so through the `AocError`, which is easily fixed.

issue_title: Theme selector
issue_body:
It is possible to change the hCaptcha theme, using the
`$Configuration['hCaptcha']['Theme'] = 'dark';` (or light instead of dark)
line in `conf/confing.php` file.
Making this configuration possible from the dashboard should be possible.

issue_title: Empty string values are converted to 'nan' as text
issue_body: Currently, empty string values are converted to 'nan' as text. The values should be converted to None instead.

issue_title: openmediavault.postinst fails due to chronyd refusing to start on systems running a kernel with SECCOMP disabled
issue_body:
This is about the following error:

```
[..]
Setting up Salt environment ...
Processing system modifications ...
dpkg: error processing package openmediavault (--configure):
 installed openmediavault package post-installation script subprocess returned error exit status 1

Errors were encountered while processing:
 openmediavault
```

due to this line in `openmediavault.postinst`:

```
omv-salt deploy run --no-color --quiet collectd chrony postfix
```

Resources for this issue so far:

<https://forum.openmediavault.org/index.php?thread/31985-solved-openmediavault-package-post-installation-script-subprocess-error/>
<https://forum.openmediavault.org/index.php?thread/32518-chronyd-fails-to-start-service-chronyd-4458-fatal-error-failed-to-load-seccomp-r/>
<https://gist.github.com/jjakob/c9ab333d15105b986008863e9f4f5db8>

Example: When filtering for `man`, match not only `bundles/admin/user-manager` but also `bundles/manager/foo`.

issue_title: "Open bundle" command: Don't display bundle name (again) in details
issue_body:
Currently a line in the "Open bundle" pick list readlike this:

> **manager** bundles/manager
> **manager-ui** bundles/manager-ui
> **fooo-manager** bundles/fooo-manager
> **ba-manager-ar** bundles/ba-manager-ar

If the details ("bundles/manager") wouldn't contain the bundle name again, you could more easisly see, which bundles are in the same folder.

Compare the above to this:

> **manager** bundles/
> **manager-ui** bundles/
> **fooo-manager** bundles/
> **ba-manager-ar** bundles/

issue_title: Bug: commetns(tokenize) bug
Validator on field defined with Union of arbitrary type and with default value raises ConfigError
issue_body:
# Question

Hi, 
I wonder if the behavior below results from a bug or me missing a point. 
A clarification would be appreciated.
Thanks

Output of `python -c "import pydantic.utils; print(pydantic.utils.version_info())"`:
```
pydantic version: 1.3
pydantic compiled: False
install path: ~/miniconda3/lib/python3.8/site-packages/pydantic
python version: 3.8.0 | packaged by conda-forge | (default, Nov 22 2019, 19:11:19)  [Clang 9.0.0 (tags/RELEASE_900/final)]
platform: macOS-10.13.6-x86_64-i386-64bit
optional deps. installed: []
```

Customize pydantic BaseConfig and define arbitrary class _Test_:
```py
from pydantic import BaseModel, validator, Field, BaseConfig
from typing import Union, Type

BaseConfig.arbitrary_types_allowed = True 

class Test:
	pass
```

Defining class _A_ without validator works: 
```
class A(BaseModel):
	view: Union[Type[Test], str] = Test
```

Defining class _A_ with a validator fails:
```
class A(BaseModel):

	view: Union[Type[Test], str] = Test

	@validator("view")
	def validate(cls, v):
		return v
```

With the following error:
```
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ConfigError                               Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-2-72c9cde31275> in <module>
----> 1 class A(BaseModel):
      2 
      3         view: Union[Type[Test], str] = Test
      4 
      5         @validator("view")

~/miniconda3/lib/python3.8/site-packages/pydantic/main.py in __new__(mcs, name, bases, namespace, **kwargs)
    221         if _custom_root_type:
    222             validate_custom_root_type(fields)
--> 223         vg.check_for_unused()
    224         if config.json_encoders:
    225             json_encoder = partial(custom_pydantic_encoder, config.json_encoders)

~/miniconda3/lib/python3.8/site-packages/pydantic/class_validators.py in check_for_unused(self)
    171         if unused_validators:
    172             fn = ', '.join(unused_validators)
--> 173             raise ConfigError(
    174                 f"Validators defined with incorrect fields: {fn} "  # noqa: Q000
    175                 f"(use check_fields=False if you're inheriting from the model and intended this)"

ConfigError: Validators defined with incorrect fields: validate (use check_fields=False if you're inheriting from the model and intended this)
```

Setting the default value to _Field(Test)_ avoids the ConfigError:
```
class A(BaseModel):

	view: Union[Type[Test], str] = Field(Test)

	@validator("view")
	def validate(cls, v):
		return v
```

issue_title: Subclass to a class inheriting from GenericModel - no validation at instantiation
issue_body:
# Bug

There is a bug, or maybe a feature request, with inheritance and Generics.

If I define a class that inherits from GenericModel and a subclass, then when I instanciate the subclass there is no check on the generic type.

From what I saw in the code, it is because the checks are done in the metaclass `__new__` method (generics are treated as `Optional[Any]` at that point), and the generic type is defined afterwards, in the `__getitem__` method.

Output of `python -c "import pydantic.utils; print(pydantic.utils.version_info())"`:
```
             pydantic version: 1.4
            pydantic compiled: False
                 install path: $HOME/envs/thenv/lib/python3.7/site-packages/pydantic
               python version: 3.7.3 (v3.7.3:ef4ec6ed12, Mar 25 2019, 16:52:21)  [Clang 6.0 (clang-600.0.57)]
                     platform: Darwin-19.3.0-x86_64-i386-64bit
     optional deps. installed: ['typing-extensions']
```

## This test passes - no inheritance

```py
def test_case_no_inheritance():
    TypeX = TypeVar('TypeX')

    SampleTypeX = list

    class MyBaseClass(GenericModel, Generic[TypeX]):
        X: TypeX

    with pytest.raises(pydantic.error_wrappers.ValidationError):
        MyBaseClass[SampleTypeX](X=1)
```

## Failed test case - inheritance

```py
import pydantic
from pydantic.main import ModelMetaclass
from pydantic.generics import GenericModel
import pytest

def test_case():
    TypeX = TypeVar('TypeX')

    SampleTypeX = list

    class MyBaseClass(GenericModel, Generic[TypeX]):
        X: TypeX

    class ExampleMeta(ModelMetaclass):
        # This metaclass is not necessary for the test, it illustrates that we get the 'generic_type' in __getitem__
        def __getitem__(self, generic_type):
            return type('Example', (Example,), {'_my_types': (SampleTypeX, generic_type)})

    class Example(MyBaseClass[TypeX], metaclass=ExampleMeta):
        pass

    Example[SampleTypeX](X=[0, 1, 2])

    with pytest.raises(pydantic.error_wrappers.ValidationError):
        Example[SampleTypeY](X=1)

```

import PySimpleGUI as sg

issue_title: Improve logging subsystem
issue_body:
We should replace the current printf-based logger with a structured logger.

Ideally any logger we'd use would:

* provide categories as a first-class feature
* support structured logging
* support logging to multiple outputs (ie. stdout + file)
* support good formatting of F# values
* be configurable in terms of which categories are logged and which log levels are written

To fulfill all of those requirements I suggest using [Serilog](https://github.com/serilog/serilog), through the [fsliblog](https://github.com/TheAngryByrd/FsLibLog) facade with the [F# support](https://github.com/destructurama/fsharp/) library.

As far as configuration, I'd add something like the following configuration to the current F# config (obsoleteing some of the existing settings):

```json
{
  "logging": {
	"level": "<log level string>",
    "include_categories": ["<list of categories to log at the above log level _only_ >"] | { "<category>": "<log level>" },  // list of categories would need to be documented somewhere
    "exclude_categories": ["<list of categories to never log>"],
    "logOutputs": [ "stdout", "file" ]
}
```

issue_title: Display warning message if module to load/unload is already loaded/unloaded
issue_body:
As [described](https://sourceforge.net/p/modules/mailman/modules-interest/thread/3EEB2422-4AE2-4CBE-B803-54CB531DA26E%40pawsey.org.au/#msg36396987) by @mcytu, it would be nice to get a warning message when a `module unload` does not unload anything because the specified module is not loaded.

Following the same trend, it would also be nice to get this kind of warning when a `module load` does not load anything as specified module is already loaded.

The idea here is to add a `./configure` option, a `MODULES_` environment variable and a command-line switch for `load`, `unload` and `switch` commands to control whether or not a warning message should be printed if a module to load or unload is already loaded or unloaded

issue_title: Execution stepping from the suspended state
issue_body:
It would be useful to have a command to step execution analogous to the step commands in gdb.  From suspended, it could step execution by one basic block.  There are a lot of different variants that seem useful:
- Continue until next merge
- Step next block
- Step out of current function (i.e., to the next return frame)

The semantics seem tricky given the postdominator-based merging that is the default in Crucible.  We would have to answer questions about the different behaviors in the DFS vs merging execution strategies.

issue_title: Different results on Windows and Mac with timestamp columns
issue_body:
Hi, I'm seeing inconsistencies with how `timestamp without time zone` columns behave on Mac and Windows when `Sys.getenv("TZ")` is different than `Sys.timezone()`. Tested on version 1.1.1.

Here's a minimal script to reproduce:

```r
library(DBI)

print(Sys.timezone()) # America/Los_Angeles
Sys.setenv(TZ="America/New_York") # another time zone

db <- dbConnect(RPostgres::Postgres(), dbname="rpostgres_test")

dbExecute(db, "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS events")
dbExecute(db, "CREATE TABLE events (created_at TIMESTAMP)")
dbExecute(db, "INSERT INTO events VALUES ('2018-01-01 12:30:00')")

rs <- dbSendQuery(db, "SELECT * FROM events")
records <- dbFetch(rs)
print(records$created_at)
```

- On Mac (as well as with RPostgreSQL), this produces `2018-01-01 12:30:00 EST`.
- On Windows, the same code produces `2018-01-01 3:30:00 EST` (when `Sys.timezone()` is `America/Los_Angeles`). 

What seems to be happening is on Mac, `2018-01-01 12:30:00` in the database is read in the `TZ` time zone. On Windows, `2018-01-01 12:30:00` in the database is read in the `Sys.timezone()` time zone, then converted to the `TZ` time zone for display.

issue_title: Timestamp without time zone problem
issue_body:
I have a database with a column of type "timestamp without time zone".
    
Times reported by that column are converted to the local timezone by RPostgres even though the server runs UTC.
    
Here's an example:
    
```{r}
library(DBI)
con <- dbConnect(RPostgres::Postgres())
    
print.default(dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT CAST('2010-06-01 00:00:00' AS timestamp) AS timestamp")$timestamp)
#> [1] 1275343200
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt" 
    
print.default(dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT extract(epoch from CAST('2010-06-01 00:00:00' AS timestamp)) as epoch")$epoch)
#> [1] 1275350400
```
The last value is the correct epoch for 2010-06-01 00:00:00 UTC.

I think the problem is related to `as.POSIXct` having `tz=""` as default, ie converting using the local timezone, but RPostgres uses "UTC" in the connection by default.
    
At least this shows the same:
    
```{r}
print.default(as.POSIXct("2010-06-01 00:00:00"))
#> [1] 1275343200
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt" 
#> attr(,"tzone")
#> [1] ""

print.default(as.POSIXct("2010-06-01 00:00:00", tz="UTC"))
#> [1] 1275350400
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt" 
#> attr(,"tzone")
#> [1] "UTC"
```
    
I suggest RPostgres should use `as.POSIXct()` with `tz="UTC"` (actually the value of `timezone` in dbConnect) when converting values from a column of type "timestamp without time zone".

The problem goes away if timestamp with time zone is used:

```
print.default(dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT CAST('2010-06-01 00:00:00' AS timestamp with time zone) AS timestamp")$timestamp)
#> [1] 1275350400
#> attr(,"class")
#> [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt" 
```

issue_title: dbGetQuery assuming postgres database is in UTC?
issue_body:
Using Rpostgres, my R session defaults to "America/Toronto" timezone, and the Postgres database I am working with is in UTC-04 by default. I'm finding that even if I change the session time zone in Postgres to "localtime" (which helps WHERE statements work correctly), dbGetQuery() still shifts the time down four hours when displaying it in R. 

Does dbGetQuery() and company just always assume the Postgres database is 'UTC' no matter what the actual Postgres session time zone is set to? 

I noticed a fix on another manifestation of dbConnect() in the odbc world [here](https://github.com/r-dbi/odbc/commit/fcba5dc96d5aeee06695183b391d8cdf6320dc40#diff-ea07e821ea0259e09f1a87f93ab1d831), so I wondered if it was a universal issue related to the generic method. 

Here is an example: 

```
library(Rpostgres)
con_pg <- dbConnect(RPostgres::Postgres())

#default R session time zone
Sys.timezone()
#> [1] "America/Toronto"


#some fake dates (one without and one with time zone)
dbExecute(con_pg, "DROP table IF EXISTS development.test")
#> [1] 0

dbExecute(
  con_pg,
  "CREATE TABLE development.test
  (
  ts_naked timestamp without time zone,
  ts_tz timestamp with time zone
  );"
)
#> [1] 0

dbExecute(con_pg, 
"INSERT INTO
development.test (ts_naked, ts_tz)
VALUES
(TIMESTAMP '2016-08-12 10:00:00-04',
  TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE '2016-08-12 10:00:00-04')")
#> [1] 1

#So weird 
dbGetQuery(con_pg, "select * from development.test WHERE ts_naked = ts_tz")
#> [1] ts_naked ts_tz   
#> <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)

#R seems to shift UP the time in Postgres 
#even though data isn't being passed between the two systems
dbGetQuery(con_pg, "select * from development.test WHERE ts_naked = ts_tz - interval '4h'")
#>              ts_naked               ts_tz
#> 1 2016-08-12 10:00:00 2016-08-12 10:00:00

#set postgres session timezone to local time (as seen in earlier issues)
dbExecute(con_pg, "set timezone to 'localtime'")
#> [1] 0

dbGetQuery(con_pg, "show timezone")
#>    TimeZone
#> 1 localtime

#The WHERE statement now works even though the ts_tz is displayed as four hours earlier by R
dbGetQuery(con_pg, "select * from development.test WHERE ts_naked = ts_tz")
#>              ts_naked               ts_tz
#> 1 2016-08-12 10:00:00 2016-08-12 06:00:00

#Setting the R session environment to UTC seems to fix it
Sys.setenv(TZ="UTC")

dbGetQuery(con_pg, "select * from development.test WHERE ts_naked = ts_tz")
#>              ts_naked               ts_tz
#> 1 2016-08-12 10:00:00 2016-08-12 10:00:00

dbGetQuery(con_pg, "select EXTRACT(TIMEZONE from ts_tz) from development.test")
#>   date_part
#> 1    -14400
```

issue_title: Incorrect results when aggregating timestamp to date
issue_body:
There seems to be a problem with RPostgres when retrieving results involving aggregating `timestamp with time zone` columns to date. The SQL that is generated (displayed with `show_query()`) yields a different result than what is actually retrieved by RPostgres. RPostgreSQL generates the same SQL, and retrieves the correct result.

In the following example, focus on the 2019-05-01 data, which should have a minimum of 24 and a maximum of 47.

```{r}
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(RPostgres)

conn <- dbConnect(Postgres(),
                  host = "dbhost",
                  user = "dbuser",
                  dbname = "dbname")

example <- tibble(val = seq(0:70)) %>%
    mutate(ts = ymd_hms("2019-04-30 00:00:00", tz = "US/Alaska") + hours(val))

example %>%
    mutate(dte = date(ts)) %>%
    group_by(dte) %>%
    summarize(min = min(val, na.rm = TRUE),
              max = max(val, na.rm = TRUE))
```

That yields the correct result:

```
  dte          min   max
  <date>     <int> <int>
1 2019-04-30     1    23
2 2019-05-01    24    47
3 2019-05-02    48    71
```

If we round-trip this through the database we get a different answer:

```{r}
dbWriteTable(conn, "example", example,
             overwrite = TRUE, append = FALSE)

conn %>%
    tbl("example") %>%
    mutate(dte = date(ts)) %>%
    group_by(dte) %>%
    summarize(min = min(val, na.rm = TRUE),
              max = max(val, na.rm = TRUE))
```

Here's the result. The values for min and max appear to be off by 8 hours as though it's treating the timestamp of the data in the database as UTC (rather than US/Alaska).

```
  dte          min   max
  <date>     <int> <int>
1 2019-04-30     1    15
2 2019-05-02    40    63
3 2019-05-03    64    71
4 2019-05-01    16    39
```

It's not the query that is generated, which gives the correct result when run inside Postgres. I get the same query when I load RPostgreSQL and use it's database driver, but it loads the proper results.

Here's the `show_query()` output:

```
<SQL>
SELECT "dte", MIN("val") AS "min", MAX("val") AS "max"
FROM (SELECT "val", "ts", date("ts") AS "dte"
FROM "example") "dbplyr_057"
GROUP BY "dte"
```

And the results of that query when run inside the database using `psql`:

```
    dte     | min | max
------------+-----+-----
 2019-04-30 |   1 |  23
 2019-05-01 |  24 |  47
 2019-05-02 |  48 |  71
```

    "rules": {
        "require-atomic-updates": "error",
    }
};
```

</details>

**What did you do? Please include the actual source code causing the issue, as well as the command that you used to run ESLint.**

<!-- Paste the source code below: -->
```js
async function f(foo) {
    let buz = await get(foo.id);
    foo.bar = buz.bar;
}
```

<!-- Paste the command you used to run ESLint: -->
```bash
./node_modules/.bin/eslint index.js
```

**What did you expect to happen?**

no errors

**I wonder why this case has to report an error!**

I use @babel/plugin-transform-async-to-generator plugin to transform the code, there are no variables be cached in context.

So it is never to cause race condition bugs.

```js
"use strict";

function asyncGeneratorStep(gen, resolve, reject, _next, _throw, key, arg) { try { var info = gen[key](arg); var value = info.value; } catch (error) { reject(error); return; } if (info.done) { resolve(value); } else { Promise.resolve(value).then(_next, _throw); } }

function _asyncToGenerator(fn) { return function () { var self = this, args = arguments; return new Promise(function (resolve, reject) { var gen = fn.apply(self, args); function _next(value) { asyncGeneratorStep(gen, resolve, reject, _next, _throw, "next", value); } function _throw(err) { asyncGeneratorStep(gen, resolve, reject, _next, _throw, "throw", err); } _next(undefined); }); }; }

function f(_x) {
  return _f.apply(this, arguments);
}

function _f() {
  _f = _asyncToGenerator( /*#__PURE__*/regeneratorRuntime.mark(function _callee(foo) {
    var buz;
    return regeneratorRuntime.wrap(function _callee$(_context) {
      while (1) {
        switch (_context.prev = _context.next) {
          case 0:
            _context.next = 2;
            return get(foo.id);

          case 2:
            buz = _context.sent;
            foo.bar = buz.bar;

          case 4:
          case "end":
            return _context.stop();
        }
      }
    }, _callee);
  }));
  return _f.apply(this, arguments);
}
```

**What actually happened? Please include the actual, raw output from ESLint.**

Possible race condition: `foo.bar` might be reassigned based on an outdated value of `foo.bar`.
```

issue_title: Consider changing default location of `.eslintcache` to `node_modules/.cache`
issue_body:
**The version of ESLint you are using.**

v7.14.0

**The problem you want to solve.**

The default location of `.eslintcache` in the project root is problematic because that directory is generally used to store configuration, not ephemeral files like this cache. By putting it in the project root, you're forcing everyone wo enables that cache to put an entry for it in `.gitignore`.

**Your take on the correct solution to problem.**

 Use [find-cache-dir](https://github.com/avajs/find-cache-dir) to locate the common cache directory and store the file there instead. This is a common pattern used by many other modules like `babel-loader`, `terser-webpack-plugin` and even `eslint-loader`. If there is no `node_modules`, fall back to a temporary directory.

**Are you willing to submit a pull request to implement this change?**

Yes

issue_title: [Bug] Spectral Mixture kernel raw_samples and train_X has to be the same as batch_size
issue_body:
# 🐛 Bug

So it seems it is not possible to use the SpectralMixtureKernel with a different amount of raw_samples (in the acquisition function) compared to the batch_size and size of training data (train_X)

This seems like a bug to me. As is it is possible for other kernels. Or am I doing something wrong here?

## To reproduce

** Code snippet to reproduce **
```python
# This breaks

import torch
from botorch.models import SingleTaskGP
from botorch.fit import fit_gpytorch_model
from botorch.utils import standardize, sampling
from gpytorch.mlls import ExactMarginalLogLikelihood
from botorch.optim import optimize_acqf
from botorch.acquisition import UpperConfidenceBound

train_X = torch.rand(1, 10, 2)

Y = 1 - torch.norm(train_X - 0.5, dim=-1, keepdim=True)
Y = Y + 0.1 * torch.randn_like(Y)  # add some noise
train_Y = standardize(Y)

gp = SingleTaskGP(train_X, train_Y)
gp.covar_module = ScaleKernel(
            SpectralMixtureKernel(
                batch_size = 10,
                ard_num_dims=train_X.shape[-1],
                num_mixtures=5),
            )
mll = ExactMarginalLogLikelihood(gp.likelihood, gp)
fit_gpytorch_model(mll)

UCB = UpperConfidenceBound(gp, beta=0.1)


bounds = torch.stack([torch.zeros(2), torch.ones(2)])
candidate, acq_value = optimize_acqf(
    UCB, bounds=bounds, q=1, num_restarts=10, raw_samples=10,
)
print(candidate) 

# While making sure that raw_samples, batch_size and train_X has the same dimensions, it works.

import torch
from botorch.models import SingleTaskGP
from botorch.fit import fit_gpytorch_model
from botorch.utils import standardize, sampling
from gpytorch.mlls import ExactMarginalLogLikelihood
from botorch.optim import optimize_acqf
from botorch.acquisition import UpperConfidenceBound

train_X = torch.rand(10, 10, 2)

Y = 1 - torch.norm(train_X - 0.5, dim=-1, keepdim=True)
Y = Y + 0.1 * torch.randn_like(Y)  # add some noise
train_Y = standardize(Y)

gp = SingleTaskGP(train_X, train_Y)
gp.covar_module = ScaleKernel(
            SpectralMixtureKernel(
                batch_size = 10,
                ard_num_dims=train_X.shape[-1],
                num_mixtures=5),
            )
mll = ExactMarginalLogLikelihood(gp.likelihood, gp)
fit_gpytorch_model(mll)

UCB = UpperConfidenceBound(gp, beta=0.1)


bounds = torch.stack([torch.zeros(2), torch.ones(2)])
candidate, acq_value = optimize_acqf(
    UCB, bounds=bounds, q=1, num_restarts=10, raw_samples=10,
)
print(candidate) 

```
** Stack trace/error message **
```
RuntimeError: The SpectralMixtureKernel expected the input to have a batch_size of torch.Size([10]) (based on the batch_size argument). Got torch.Size([1]).
```

## Expected Behavior

I want to use a Spectral mixture kernel where I have a different amount of training data compared to the raw_samples I want to analyse with my acquisition function. This does seem to work for the other Kernels I have tested but not for Spectral mixture kernels.

## System information

**Please complete the following information:**
-  BoTorch Version 0.1.4 
- GPyTorch Version 0.3.6 
-  PyTorch Version 1.4.0 
- Mojave

## Additional context

Add any other context about the problem here.

issue_title: wdel.time(0) to auto-set the loop-size for C3
issue_body:
Specifically for tuned-delay-line usage, it will be helpful to have `ii.wdel.time(0)` to set the length of the delay buffer such that `ii.wdel.freq(0)` results in C3 (or C4). This means the delay line can be played in tune with wsyn & jf, maintaining the 0V reference across the different modules.

This is easy to implement (and should be done asap, because of that), but will need to be recalculated after fixing the circular-buffer handling.
